ution\nof $\\varphi$ at very early times may tune the rate of baryogenesis.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Jul 2019 07:50:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 20 Sep 2019 17:42:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-10-09"}
{"id":"1907.06354","submitter":"Adam Bednorz","authors":"Stanis{\\l}aw So{\\l}tan, Mateusz Fr\\k{a}czak, Wolfgang Belzig, Adam\n  Bednorz","title":"Conservation laws in quantum noninvasive measurements","comments":"8 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Research 3, 013247 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevResearch.3.013247","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Conservation principles are essential to describe and quantify dynamical\nprocesses in all areas of physics. Classically, a conservation law holds\nbecause the description of reality can be considered independent of an\nobservation (measurement). In quantum mechanics, however, invasive observations\nchange quantities drastically, irrespective of any classical conservation law.\nOne may hope to overcome this nonconservation by performing a weak, almost\nnoninvasive measurement. Interestingly, we find that the nonconservation is\nmanifest even in weakly measured correlations if some of the other observables\ndo not commute with the conserved quantity. Our observations show that\nconservation laws in quantum mechanics should be considered in their specific\nmeasurement context. We provide experimentally feasible examples to observe the\napparent nonconservation of energy and angular momentum.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Jul 2019 07:55:44 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 24 Sep 2019 10:41:18 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 18 Dec 2019 21:55:42 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Mon, 4 May 2020 07:42:35 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Mon, 6 Jul 2020 05:23:17 GMT"},{"version":"v6","created":"Fri, 19 Mar 2021 10:47:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-03-24"}
